# URLs lychee must not try to resolve. One regex per line.
#
# 1. Hosts with no dot in them are never internet URLs. Two sources in this repo, both
#    uncheckable from CI by construction:
#      a) Cluster-internal service names in Gateway/HTTPRoute manifests and in the DR
#         runbook — https://budget/, https://dex/, https://backstage/. They resolve only
#         inside the cluster.
#      b) Mis-parses of cosign keyless-identity REGEXES. lychee stops at the backslash, so
#         '^https://token\.actions\.githubusercontent\.com$' is reported as https://token/
#         and '^https://github\.com/...' as https://github/. These are signature-verification
#         patterns, not links — rewriting them to satisfy a link checker would break image
#         verification.
^https?://[^./]+/?$

# 2. Private ingress hostnames. They resolve on the home network only.
^https?://.*\.lan(/|$)
^https?://.*\.svc\.cluster\.local(/|$)
^https?://dex\.dev\.platform\.devantler\.tech(/|$)

# 3. Shell and Actions variables interpolated into a URL. lychee percent-encodes the braces, so
#    ${KSAIL_VERSION} arrives as %7BKSAIL_VERSION%7D and the URL can never resolve — the real one
#    only exists at run time, once the version is substituted.
%7B

# 4. RFC 5737 TEST-NET-1. Reserved for documentation and unroutable by design; ci.yaml uses it as
#    a deliberately dead API-server address.
^https?://192\.0\.2\.

# 5. An OIDC issuer IDENTIFIER, not a browsable page. Discovery lives at
#    /.well-known/openid-configuration; the root path is expected to 404. This value must match
#    GitHub's issuer string exactly, so it is not editable to please a link checker.
^https://token\.actions\.githubusercontent\.com/?$

# 6. A third-party status badge in the README. It returns 500 intermittently; its availability is
#    not something this repository can fix, and it must never gate a merge.
^https://api\.star-history\.com/
